            "id": "c93765de1e9c494d83ced",
            "questionText": "An electron is confined within a one-dimensional quantum dot of length $!$L = 5 \\text{ nm}$!$. Assuming the electron behaves as a wave described by the de Broglie hypothesis and that its orbit equals twice the length of the quantum dot, determine the electron's velocity given Planck's constant $!$h = 6.626 \\times 10^{-34} \\text{ Js}$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "dcc0086906734c8395ef8",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by considering the standing wave condition for an electron confined in a one-dimensional box. Identify the correct relationship between the wavelength $!$\\lambda$!$ and the length $!$L$!$ of the quantum dot, given that the orbit equals twice the dot's length.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = 2L$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = L$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = L/2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "81984d25d1f5405db41ca",
                    "stepText": "Great. Now, using the selected relation and the given length $!$L = 5 \\times 10^{-9}$!$ m, calculate the electron's wavelength $!$\\lambda$!$. (Remember to substitute the value for $!$L$!$ properly.)",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1e-8"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "4d63e76c315049f0a69e8",
                    "stepText": "Next, let\u2019s use the de Broglie relation to connect the momentum of the electron with its wavelength. Please choose the formula that correctly relates the momentum $!$p$!$, Planck's constant $!$h$!$, and the wavelength $!$\\lambda$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "6ebe6c0d-c162-454d-9895-d18bb1afb5b9"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p = \\frac{h}{\\lambda}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p = h \\times \\lambda$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$p = \\frac{\\lambda}{h}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "359527413f0f47dbadd7a",
                    "stepText": "Using the correct relation from the previous step and the given value $!$h = 6.626 \\times 10^{-34}$!$ J\\,s, along with the wavelength you computed, calculate the electron's momentum $!$p$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "6.626e-26"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kg\\,m/s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "6ebe6c0d-c162-454d-9895-d18bb1afb5b9"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "e93bd8c7d74a4505b12ee",
                    "stepText": "Now, let's link the electron's momentum to its velocity. Choose the appropriate formula that connects momentum $!$p$!$, electron mass $!$m$!$, and velocity $!$v$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\frac{p}{m}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\frac{m}{p}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = p \\times m$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "911f6c8a15834242b40cb",
                    "stepText": "Finally, use the relation from the previous step to compute the electron's velocity $!$v$!$, using the momentum you calculated ($!$6.626 \\times 10^{-26}$!$ kg\\,m/s) and the electron mass $!$m = 9.11 \\times 10^{-31}$!$ kg.",
