        {
            "id": "b5cad2f2fa0d42f4bb60f",
            "questionText": "A photodetector in a telescope uses a metal with a work function $!$\\phi = 2.5 \\text{ eV}$!$. The detector is exposed to light from a distant galaxy with a frequency $!$f = 8 \\times 10^{14} \\text{ Hz}$!$. Calculate the stopping voltage $!$V_s$!$ required to halt the emitted photoelectrons. Use the relations $!$E_{photoelectron} = hf - \\phi$!$, $!$E = e V_s$!$, Planck's constant $!$h = 6.626 \\times 10^{-34} \\text{ Js}$!$, and the conversion $!$1 \\text{ eV} = 1.602 \\times 10^{-19} \\text{ J}$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "4291cdd1658046d39492d",
